---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Home">
  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto py-10 px-4 landing-content">

    <!-- Opening -->
    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary leading-tight mb-6">
        AI adoption doesn't start with tools.<br />It starts with understanding your work.
      </h1>

      <p>
        Every organisation is being told to "use AI." But when you actually sit down to figure out where it fits, the picture gets complicated fast. Which processes should you touch? How much should AI actually do? What needs to stay with people? And how do you test any of this without putting your operations, your data or your reputation at risk?
      </p>

      <p>
        The reality is that everyone's work is a mix. Routine stuff that just needs doing, and moments where judgement, context and accountability actually matter. AI is exceptionally good at the first part. The risk is letting it bleed into the second without thinking it through.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- AI is not one thing -->
    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>AI is not one thing</h2>

      <p>
        You have probably seen demos of "AI agents" that seem to do everything. Enrich your leads. Write your reports. Manage your content pipeline. But what looks like one intelligent system is actually a combination of different components working together.
      </p>

      <p>
        Under the hood, a typical AI system includes: a language model that understands and generates text, deterministic tools that do exact things like query a database or run a calculation, a retrieval layer that looks up information from your documents and human checkpoints where a person reviews, approves or redirects. Each component has different strengths and different failure modes. How you put them together matters as much as which ones you pick.
      </p>

      <p>
        That is why adopting AI is not just a technology decision. Work is done by people, in context, with informal knowledge and judgement. Technology is fast and consistent but blind to all of that. Getting this right means looking at both sides and figuring out where they fit together. This guide helps you do that.
      </p>

      <p>
        You do not need to be technical. You do not need to know which model to use. You just need a workflow you are curious about.
      </p>

      <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 1.5rem;">
        <a href={`${base}1-discover/`} class="cta-link">Start the guide &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- What you'll do -->
    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>What this guide walks you through</h2>

      <div class="guide-steps">
        <div class="guide-step">
          <span class="guide-num">1</span>
          <div>
            <p class="step-title">Where are the real opportunities?</p>
            <p class="step-desc">Learn how to find the workflows worth looking at. Not every problem needs AI.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <span class="guide-num">2</span>
          <div>
            <p class="step-title">Pick a workflow</p>
            <p class="step-desc">Choose one of four built-in scenarios or describe your own. Start with the pain, not the solution.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <span class="guide-num">3</span>
          <div>
            <p class="step-title">Is it ready to pilot?</p>
            <p class="step-desc">Score it against practical criteria. Some ideas sound great but are not ready for a test yet.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <span class="guide-num">4</span>
          <div>
            <p class="step-title">What components do you need?</p>
            <p class="step-desc">Map the ingredients: what needs a language model, what needs deterministic logic, what needs retrieval, where do humans stay in the loop.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <span class="guide-num">5</span>
          <div>
            <p class="step-title">What could go wrong?</p>
            <p class="step-desc">Each component has specific failure modes. Put checks in place: what the system cannot do, where humans must approve, what happens when something fails.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <span class="guide-num">6</span>
          <div>
            <p class="step-title">Build the pilot plan</p>
            <p class="step-desc">Assemble everything into a roadmap and a build brief you can hand to a developer or an AI assistant.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <span class="guide-num">7</span>
          <div>
            <p class="step-title">Did it work?</p>
            <p class="step-desc">Measure what changed. Faster is not enough if you lost control. Then decide: scale, revise or stop.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- What you walk away with -->
    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>What you walk away with</h2>

      <p>
        By the end of this guide, you'll have:
      </p>

      <ul class="takeaway-list">
        <li>A clear picture of which parts of your workflow need AI, which need plain automation and which need people</li>
        <li>A component map showing what you need to build: language models, tools, retrieval, human checkpoints and how they connect</li>
        <li>A boundary checklist covering what the system cannot do, where humans must approve and what happens when things fail</li>
        <li>A pilot roadmap with evaluation criteria and a timeline</li>
        <li>A build brief you can hand to a developer or paste into an AI assistant to get implementation options</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        You can try the guide with one of four built-in scenarios or bring your own workflow. Everything runs in your browser. The AI analysis feature uses a hosted service but no data is stored.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <div class="text-center mb-10">
      <a href={`${base}1-discover/`} class="cta-link">Start the guide →</a>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- About + feedback -->
    <div class="mb-8">
      <h2>About this project</h2>

      <p>
        I built this because I kept seeing the same gap. Organisations want to use AI but don't have a practical way to evaluate where it actually fits. The existing options are either too abstract, too technical or too focused on selling tools.
      </p>

      <p>
        This guide is open source, free and a work in progress. I'm actively developing it and would genuinely appreciate feedback. If something doesn't make sense, if a step feels wrong or if you have ideas for how to make it more useful, I'd love to hear from you.
      </p>

      <div class="feedback-links">
        <a href="mailto:kevin.witzenberger@posteo.de" class="link link-primary">Send me feedback</a>
        <span class="text-base-content/30">|</span>
        <a href="https://github.com/kevinwtz404/adoption-eval" class="link link-primary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View on GitHub</a>
        <span class="text-base-content/30">|</span>
        <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/kevin-witzenberger/" class="link link-primary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Connect on LinkedIn</a>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .landing-content p {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .landing-content h2 {
    font-size: 1.375rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .step-title {
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .step-desc {
    font-size: 15px;
    color: var(--text-light);
    margin-top: 0.125rem;
  }

  .takeaway-list {
    list-style: disc;
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    margin: 0.75rem 0 1.25rem;
  }

  .takeaway-list li {
    font-size: 15px;
    padding: 0.3rem 0;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .cta-link {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.6rem 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--purple);
    border-radius: 8px;
    color: var(--purple);
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: all 0.15s;
  }

  .cta-link:hover {
    background: var(--purple);
    color: white;
  }

  .feedback-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-top: 1rem;
    font-size: 15px;
  }
</style>
